The barn that holds all of the stories. 

The barn that my grandpa milked cows in. He wasn’t very fond of cows. 

The barn my Dad spent his teenage years in. Getting up before school to milk cows, only to do it again when the bus dropped him off. 

The barn that brought family together, and tore them apart somedays. 

A barn that is now used for storage of all things, full of cobwebs, and barn cats. 

Somedays I go inside that barn and think about what it was like. My family built our parlor the year I was born, so I never saw this barn in action. I can only imagine what it was like, from all of the stories my family tells.

Our first official year with GPS. Here’s how it went ⬇️

Our guidance systems were installed last fall. We can’t lie, we were a little timid at first to use something that can basically change course of your whole tractor. That feeling immediately went away for us when we got comfortable using our @agleadertech. As we plugged away at the fields we quickly realized that this is possibly one of the best farm investments one could make. 

Looking ahead, we started harvest. Although my dad likes to think he has always had straight rows, I’d beg to differ after seeing these! Linking up our grain cart to our combine with CartACE was insanely efficient. I am a believer in ag technology after using @agleadertech for one year. 

If you’re unfamiliar with CartACE, please refer to our YT channel. I made a few videos this year explaining in depth about it. But in basic terms, the combine can see where the grain cart is in the field via satellite images, the grain cart tractor can then press a button when next to the combine, and it aligns the tractor and combine at the perfect distance to dump on the go. Incredible. 

Here’s to many more years of upgrades to efficiency!

If you deal with anxiety, panic attacks, or depression, you are not alone! 

I have pretty severe panic disorder & anxiety and while I may look like I have my shit together, I can promise you it’s a different story on the inside. 

I’ve been dealing with anxiety and panic attacks for close to 7 years. I’ve learned how to manage it with the help of my mom, therapist, and lots of learning, but I still struggle with it frequently! 

Im not huge on taking medication, and only take it when it’s really bad. 

Here are some ways I keep my anxiety and panic low:

-make lists. Write things down. Get things out of your head. It’s crazy how much the build up of things in your head can make you go into a spiral after so long. 

-talk to someone. A therapist, friend or family. You need to have a human you can just spill everything to. 

-eat less processed foods. It has seriously helped me so much. 

-listen to happy music. I hate this advice but when I’m walking along in the barns, listening to reggae, I can tell you my day goes 1000x better. 

-get off your phone and go touch the earth. Go on a walk, hug your animals, be one with nature. I don’t realize how crappy scrolling & scrolling& scrolling makes my brain feel until I’m in a field with my dog, free of any screens. 

-cut back the caffeine. Yup I said it, eek. It helps. 

-take yo vitamins! There’s a good chance your body is lacking on vitamins. Vitamins can improve your mood, keep you healthy, and so much more. I take zinc, vitamin C, b12, d3, apple pectin, and selenium. 

I share my story with anxiety and panic disorder because it’s not talked about enough in the ag industry. You can get through this, trust me, I know!

This picture is the epitome of looking happy on the outside, but falling apart on the inside. 

I took this last March, a time when I was seemingly happy ( and I was for the most part, I was having fun) but going through so much more than the eyes can see. I was at the peak of my anxiety. I remember taking this picture, my heart was racing, mind felt like I was doomed, and I could hardly breath. It was supposed to be a relaxing weekend with my cousin in her city, but instead I was fighting panic attacks the entire time. 

The drive home was hell. 5 hours of being on the verge of panic attacks. Fighting every bad thought in my mind. 

When I finally made it home, I knew something had to change for my mental health. I started working out. Eating less processed foods. Drinking less. And seeing a therapist! I was pretty anti-therapist, but she changed EVERYTHING. 

It’s been A LOT of work and I’m still not done, but my anxiety has been the most minimal it has been since sophomore year in HIGH SCHOOL! 

It’s just a reminder that just because someone looks happy on the outside, doesn’t mean they are doing okay. My mind and body were screaming for help. If you are struggling, there are ways to beat this.

After 8 years of sharing my life in ag online, I’ve been accused of “not actually caring about my animals” and even being called an animal abuser just for being a dairy farmer. 

It has become so clear to me over the last 8 years just how insanely out of touch people are. 

I’m not asking for appreciation or a thanks. I’m asking you to be more open minded so that you can face reality. 

I am a dairy farmer and I LOVE these animals. 

On Friday, I found this calf with her mother on the verge of death, and frozen. The mother had her early in the barn and the baby was hard to see. I actually walked by it once it was so camouflaged with the ground. The mom standing there like “what do I do with it” as the baby laid there like an ice cube. 

I spent 4 hours warming this baby up. A warm bath, rubbing a towel on her to stimulate blood flow, tubing her warm milk, and my final effort; the hair dryer. 

I saw death in her eyes so many times. There was a point her breathing slowed so much that I just started praying to God to keep her here. My eyes lost a lot of tears that morning. 

Hours later of fighting for the calf I now call Rudy, and she started coming back. Lifting her head, her mouth finally unclamped, and her entire body warmed up. My efforts paid off. 

So when I hear someone say farmers don’t care about their animals, I get angry. And hearing things like that from the uneducated drives me even more to share these hard stories with you. 

Once again, I am Not looking for appreciation, or a thank you, all I’m looking for is an understanding that we as farmers do what’s best for our animals AND for the business. Yes, those two things can coexist.

How to burn 367281919 calories on a farm: move weaned calves 🥵

We wean our calves off of milk at 3 months of age. We gradually give them less milk leading up to weaning day so that they don’t get stressed out when they are no longer getting milk. After they are weaned, we move them into group pens in the barn next door where they learn to eat in head locks, socialize with each other, and get used to a grain, water and TMR based diet!

“Do your cows ever go outside?!?!”

One would think seeing animals come and go on the farm gets easier each time. I’m here to tell you it doesn’t. 

Entirely heartbroken to share Indy passed away yesterday afternoon. My body aches at her loss. The ten pictures above don’t begin to share the amount of days she made my workdays significantly brighter. In 2022, I struggled with my mental health more than I ever have before. I can’t imagine what that whole year would be like without Indy by my side for each moment of every day. I feel undeserving of her loyalty and unconditional love towards me. She constantly reminded me of the little things in life like making me smile by playing with a dried up Cheeto on the floor. But also the big things in life- like patience. She is so crazy- she can run miles with no stopping in sight. I learned to give her grace and accept and learn about the tools I needed to give her to thrive. 

Sharing the story of how it happened just so in case it can save someone else’s best friend. We were doing the same side-by-side ride we do every day. At one spot in the run she goes on one side of the hedgerow to try to beat us to the opening in the field (she always does). Yesterday she turned around and instead followed us the whole way. The machine we were in had less visibility than the one we normally run. Although we were going a max of 10 MPH, we had no chance to see her come from behind, and she tried to get the tires (I’m sure all heeler owners can relate). She passed away in my arms on the way to the emergency vet. 

My heart is sincerely broken. Hug your dogs more today in thoughts of Indy.

“It’s too soon” “ I can’t replace her like this” “ What if I don’t connect with a new dog like I did with her”. The list goes on. Silencing those demons in my head wasn’t an easy feat in the slightest. 

To some, it’s just a dog. It’s just an animal. But if you’ve lost a dog you truly loved, you know exactly how I feel. I found a pain I haven’t felt before in the last few weeks without Indy. Along with that I felt regretful, guilty, at fault, shame, and even with the outpouring of love from all of you ; loneliness. 

The day we brought home Dolly I felt a spark inside of me again. Yes it was quick. Yes my heart still aches. Of course I’ve cried when I look at this darling of a puppy, but not only out of love, but the reminders of what Indy had been. 

“Puppies heal hearts” “There’s no love like that of a new puppy” “ Let her be your new motivation to get up in the morning”. And to that I say yes. She has taken on a feat that she doesn’t even know she has. My heart aches a little less and the sadness was replaced with a joyous period of time. And to that, I say thank you, Dolly. You truly will never know how much you have saved me.

Our newborn calf protocol:

-Let the mother lick it off if she’s motherly enough to do so. 

-Move calf to warm box. 

-Decide what colostrum you will be feeding calf. We either do pasteurized colostrum from the mother using our Matilda from @dairytechinc or powdered colostrum if she doesn’t produce enough/quality. 

-Feed calf colostrum within 2 hours of being born. Colostrum is the first milk that a cow produces after calving. It’s full of amazing antibodies to build the calves immune system. 

-Give new calf Inforce 3 vaccination, First defense tri-shield, and 2cc of multimin. 

-Dip calf’s naval with iodine to prevent infection.

-Mark head with paint stick so everyone on the farm knows he/she has been fed. 

-Tell the calf they are awesome and give them a kiss on the head (very important step). 

-Once calf is fed & dry move to the calf barn where he/she will live and be fed 2x a day! 

(& those aren’t new freckles on my face, thanks 5467 🙄 💩)

Here is why most dairy farmers separate the calf from the cow shortly after birth:

For the safety of the calf:
Dairy cows are not as motherly as beef cows. Just yesterday I witnessed a mother step on her own baby’s stomach. Hard. As of now we don’t think there’s any organ damage. I have seen a mother step and kill on its own baby. They are clumsy animals. I do not take chances. The calf barn is a MUCH safer place for a newborn calf. 

For the health of the calf: 
Calves are born with a very minimal immune system. We give them the perfect quantity and quality of colostrum within the first 2 hours of being born. It’s not guaranteed that the mother will produce enough or quality colostrum. We collect hers and if it’s not up to standard, we mix up replacer or use another cows colostrum. It is ESSENTIAL the baby gets the antibodies from the colostrum. We also give 3 different vaccines/pills that help build up her immune system. The calf barn is like a NICU. Clean, away from big cow germs, and safe. 

Some important things to note:
-No, the mother doesn’t yell for her calves for days on end like vegan propaganda tries to demonstrate. Most don’t care. If they do, they care for a half hour max, and then their hormones die down. Our barns are quiet. Our animals are content. 

-Yes, the baby will get moms milk. First, in the form of colostrum and then everyday for the next 3 months until they are weaned. We collect milk from the cows and put it into our mobile pasteurizer and feed it to the calves 2x a day. 

-Yes, we love our animals. They are our livelihood and I would do anything in my power to provide them a stress free life. 

The babies stay on our farm forever if they are heifers. If they are bulls we either raise them as steers or send them to other farms who raise them for beef. Simple as that. Any other questions, please ask!

Things I’ve learned dating someone in agriculture 👇🏻

Besides the obvious things like the horrendous laundry, late dinners, and early mornings, I think I’ve learned something even more important in the last (almost) 3 years with Aidan. 

Instead of feeling annoyed about his or my own hours I’ve started to think of it as a blessing. Sharing the same space in the same industry creates a whole new meaning of understanding each other. Of course the blessing stands that we also both love what we do so much, too. 

Our weather dependent hours sometimes line up great and we’re both busy the same times of year. Him talking about his day doesn’t sound completely foreign to me ( sometimes just a tad 🤏🏼😅). Looking for the positives in areas of your lives together like this is so important. 

That’s not to say I haven’t felt envy or disappointment when he has to stay home instead of going on vacations, miss family functions, or be able to do “normal” couple things in the spring and fall. It’s more that I’ve started to look at it as a good thing I can at least understand why. 

 And if you’re lucky enough to get one like mine- he might even come to the farm to pile more hours onto a 16 hour work day like he was here🧡🥹

Confidence. 

It’s a given that it’s needed if you’re involved in agriculture in anyway. Running equipment, working with large animals, being the decision maker that determines your livelihood, the list goes on really. 

There are inevitable times when farming can test our confidence. Bad weather, market prices, etc.. Having low confidence in those areas just means we need to build some more on things we CAN control. 

Confidence is key. 

Confidence is also @nkseeds_us . 

Knowing your crop will perform and having the confidence while planting it is what can make a better farmer. NK Seeds has been building our confidence for years, and it makes us look forward to planting season just that much more.

Did you know we are also asparagus farmers? 

During the month of May, our asparagus crop is in full swing. Asparagus grows out of the ground and we cut, bundle, and sell it at our farm stand. We grow purple and green varieties, but I prefer the purple, slightly sweeter!

Routines. Let’s talk about them…

My routine has been the same for a couple years now. Get up, go to school, get home, go to work then enjoy my nights doing whatever. 

Routines can either be a good thing or a bad thing depending on how you look at them, and the energy you surround yourself with. 

Me personally, I love having a good routine. Although sometimes it can get a little old due to the repetition of the same thing everyday. 

I try to do different things in my free time to keep from the repetition. Such things Include, cooking, reading, going for a run, or hanging out with my family/friends. 

In the end it all depends on how you spend your free time. 

I have been feeding calves for almost 9 years now, the repetition can get boring at times… but its the positive outlook that completely changes my perspective. 

Social media has really helped me love feeding calves more and more because I get to share all my experiences with you guys! ❤️

My relationship with God has been a roller coaster. 

I don’t talk about this much, as when I tried to in the past, I felt like I was walking on egg shells, saying things the wrong way, and just afraid of offending those who also believe. Even being corrected for not capitalizing God in one of my posts, was pointed out, and left me feeling discouraged. But, I am changing that starting right now. 

Growing up, we did not go to church. Maybe a total of 10 times in my life. I still do not go to church. My Dad’s side of the family is pretty religious. My Mom has said a few things about God growing up, but she never made it the forefront of our life growing up. Which in a weird way, I am thankful for. Because it allowed me to find God all by myself. 

In 2020, I had crippling anxiety. The world was crazy. I was way too into listening to podcasts about how our government works. I was always looking for peace whether that was in working out, eating, etc. I felt like a fragile piece of glass that could break at any second. And I did break, many times. 

This past year, the pull got so strong that I couldn’t really ignore it anymore. I bought a bible and started reading it. I had no idea why, I just felt the need to read it. 

I am no where near finished with the Bible but, I have noticed some things as I read it. I am starting to understand who God is, who Jesus is. I never even knew the difference. I learned that reading it, should never feel like a chore, so I only read on the days when I feel the intuition to do so. I am learning how much peace it brings me. 

Peace is something I have struggled to find for a while. My relationship with God brings me peace. So much of it. When I am having a panic attack, I flip to a random page, and with every word I read, my breath slows and my mind eases. 

I feel like I have abandoned my relationship with God my entire life, but there he was this whole time. Waiting for me. Rooting for me. Working behind the scenes for me. There is nothing I am more ready for than growing this relationship. The most important relationship of my life.

I SHOULD NOT EVEN HAVE TO REPEAT THIS RIGHT NOW! 

We do NOT ALLOW VISITORS! 

WE DO NOT HOLD LONG CONVERSATIONS WITH PEOPLE THROUGH ANY APPS. IF YOU THINK YOURE TALKING TO US- YOURE PROBABLY NOT! Be SMART! 

WE DO NOT GIVE OUT ANY PERSONAL INFORMATION!

WE DO NOT ASK YOU FOR PERSONAL INFO! 

Around 1pm today we had a disturbing scenario happen. A man drove all the way from OHIO to meet JoJo. Said he had been messaging her and our Dad. Showed up and started yelling at JoJo- demanding her to take him to the farm because she “promised a tour”. He exchanged money with whoever he was talking to- and full heartedly believed he was talking to JoJo. Just DUMB! We have pictures of him, along with plate numbers to show to law enforcement. Who drives 7 hours to meet a 18 year old girl when he was at least 35! 

Do not show up. Do not get scammed. We have means to protect ourselves- and never want to have to come to the point of having to protect ourselves against any CREEPS! 

This is the price we have to pay when it comes to putting our lives out there on social media and I won’t lie- it makes me want to stop doing it. 

We cannot stop you from getting scammed- so just be smarter. We have a blue check mark, that’s how you know the true verified account. And I highly don’t recommend showing up to our property unannounced. We have some pretty great people willing to go to any means to protect us. As well as the ability to protect ourselves. 

And for those who respect our boundaries, and having been loyal, lovely people, following along with our lives, thanks, you keep us going.

As a herds manager, this picture makes me so happy. Our wheat being turned into tightly packed bales. If you didn't know, we bed all of our calves, dry cows, hospital pen, and maternity pack with straw! Straw helps keep the cows clean and comfortable during each season! It's so important we have enough straw stored away to keep the cows well cared for all year.

We bale around 500 straw bales and even feed some of the straw to our dry cows! With our @case_ih baler, we are able to obtain perfectly crafted bales from our golden fields of wheat, that will last us all throughout the year. Our Case IH baler has become an essential player in one of the top priorities on our farm, cow comfort!

Is sharing your life on social media worth it? (An older sisters POV) 

On Dec. 11th,my youngest sister, JoJo, had her stalker attack her. His name will go unnamed for now, as we pursue further action. 
Flash back to last November, a man in his 20s showed up to our family home. He looked homeless, scratches all over his face, a trash bag with his belongings in his hand. Claimed to have been from California. He was looking for JoJo. This incident happened again, in a similar fashion, but this time he was dropped off by someone. He was desperately looking for my 18 year old sister. 17 at the time. He claimed that he was living in a shelter. I have no pity for him, as he still had a phone that he was using to leave disturbing comments on her videos. Looking back, we should have filed a report then and there. 

On Friday December 8th, my mom and JoJo received a phone call from the university police saying there was a man looking for JoJo on campus. When he said his name, our hearts dropped. How did he make it all the way to her school? The officer said JoJo didn’t go there, and filed for him to be banned from Campus. 

This part hurts me to write. JoJo was offered a police escort to bring her to and from places on campus so she wouldn’t have to walk alone. She had a final to take on Monday morning and it was a very short distance to walk, so she decided to do it on her own. As she was walking to her final, her stalker came at her, put his hands on her, and began saying very disturbing things. Luckily there was someone walking by (a guardian angel) and JoJo yelled to call 911 as she ran to safety. The police came and arrested him and he was brought to court. Only for him to be admitted to a hospital for psychiatric care and released that same night. Gotta love NYS! 

We are now putting forth further action. 

We share our lives on our family’s dairy farm, so simple, but I guess that means our safety is sacrificed. JoJo won’t be engaging in social media for a long time. I wouldn’t blame her if she never wanted to again. Something that we worked so hard to build for the future of agriculture, and this is what we get in return. All in all it just doesn’t seem worth it.

If you own any amount of land, Dale has a SPECIAL message for you!

If you are looking to make some extra cash without the hassle- listen up. We have been using the app iHunt for a couple of months now. As landowners, we often get knocks on our doors and endless phone calls from hunters asking to utilize our land. Thankfully since finding iHunt we haven’t had to deal with a single person hassling us for land use. 

Instead- we get a notification on our phone with the money being sent over for the use of our land. iHunt is basically an AirBnB for hunting. We list our land, hunters hop on the app, pick the day and place they want to hunt, and if it’s available that day they pay the rent fee to us, and that’s that. Seriously a game changer if you are a landowner! And- who can say no to extra cash if you have parcels of land that you’re not hunting? It’s really a no brainer.

Have you taken a look at @ihuntdoyou in your area yet? Let us know what you think!
